args:
As children, Chelle would often sit atop the
prince's back and ride him like a horse—and
she now seeks to do the same with his allies!
Though the group is surprised, Chelle explains
the trick to building a bond of trust using the
relationship between a person and a horse.
So these are the Chanzelian outskirts, eh?\nThey are quite beautiful.
Right? Funny how it was nothin' but\nsand and wasteland gettin' here.
This would be the perfect place for a\nlong ride on a good steed.
Now THAT'S an idea I can get behind!
...Okay, maybe I'm crazy but I think\nI actually HEAR a horse coming.
Well met, my new friends!\nAre you enjoying your stroll?
Hello, Chelle. Are you on a patrol,\nor just riding out to see your people?
I do not mingle with the commonfolk!\nThis is merely a ride for my own pleasure.

I often canter about upon my white steed
while taking in the Chanzelian breeze.
Oh, and of course my royal guard is
always there to accompany me.
It's rather become a part\nof my daily routine.
But ever since my beloved old horse\n{player_name} gave me the boot,\nI've no choice but to ride a real one.
Please don't bring that up again.

Although, if I could get someone to be my
horsey in your place, I could finally return
to riding about the royal court itself!
That would be very nice indeed.
...Well? What say you? Which of you lot\nwants the honor of being my new steed?
How about you, my sylvan friend?\nI assure you, I pay MOST handsomely.
No amount of money can compel me\ninto such a childish game.
If there's one thing a merc like me knows,\nit's that ya NEVER turn down a payin' job.
Hop on, Princess! I got muscles to spare,\nso I can carry ya around all day!
I would not be caught dead riding a horse\nwith a back as hard and uncomfortable\nas yours so clearly would be.
I seek a more supple, refined steed.
So this wild stallion's too much for ya?\nCan't say I agree, but yer the boss.
Ugh. I am certain you would be\na MOST unruly equine companion.
Who are you calling an unruly equine?!
That's not the part of that statement\nI thought she'd object to...
Pick me, pick me! I've got mad wings,\nwhich means I can be a FLYING horse!
You are far too small, faerie.
Were I to try to get on your back,\nwe'd both go crashing to the ground.
Oh yeah. That WOULD suck, huh?
I require a smart, swift, and tenacious\nsteed—and none of you yet fit the bill.
Yes, I must have a horse that is both\nrefined and graceful, just as I am...
Princess, you cannot seriously think to—
Ah, but I DO think, Paladyn.\nYou will be PERFECT!
P-pray reconsider!\nI would make a terrible playmate.
I'm miserable with idle banter, and I most\ncertainly cannot act in place of a horse!
Protest to your loyal heart's content;\nyou will heed my order in the end.
That said, you'd likely still disappoint,\ndespite giving your all.
The shame of that failure would linger\nand fester, your nights spent locked\nin guilt-ridden fever dreams...
Is that not the kind of person you are?
Buh... I m-mean... Of course not!
P-please, surely you have teased\nme enough...
Ah, my dear, naive brother.\nYou really don't understand, do you?
Your dear Paladyn may LOOK upset,\nbut she is actually quite happy to\nhave me prod at her in this fashion.
There are many types of horses, Brother.\nSome like to be left alone, while others\ncrave attention.
And you cannot trust that their words\nreflect the truth. Many horses struggle\nto express themselves.
You must SENSE what they wish for,\ntake their reins, and treat them in the way\nbest-suited to their particular nature.
By doing this over and over again,\na bond of trust is cultivated between\nhorse and rider. Do you understand now?
I'm not certain that applies here...
Eee hee hee! Oh, but you are still SUCH\na child in so many ways. Just bear in mind\nthe lesson I have given you this day.
Try to understand each horse's feelings as\nan individual. Only by doing so can you\nhope to run any distance with them.
